1
00:00:07,546 --> 00:00:19,956
Good morning, everyone. Before we are good afternoon, I suppose, depending on your time zone, before we get things started here, just a quick reminder to pay attention to GDC's code of conduct with all of your chat exchanges this morning.

2
00:00:20,317 --> 00:00:23,639
Just be nice, be thoughtful, not too difficult, easy stuff.

3
00:00:24,120 --> 00:00:27,663
So our speaker today is the prolific game composer, Winifred Phillips.

4
00:00:28,003 --> 00:00:33,528
You might recognize her work for franchises like Assassin's Creed, God of War, Little Big Planet, Total War and The Sims.

5
00:00:34,525 --> 00:00:35,925
We'll get started here just in a second.

6
00:00:36,426 --> 00:00:39,747
So as we do, please feel free to drop any questions you may have about the creative

7
00:00:39,787 --> 00:00:45,449
or technical challenges of game music composition or Winifred's own past work you may have in

8
00:00:45,469 --> 00:00:47,270
that questions tab in your chat window there.

9
00:00:47,290 --> 00:00:51,371
And we'll ask however many we have time for and get into talking about those.

10
00:00:51,451 --> 00:00:53,632
So with that, Winifred, you ready to get started here?

11
00:00:54,750 --> 00:00:58,192
I'm looking forward to it. Hello GDC summer. This is going to be fun.

12
00:00:58,613 --> 00:01:04,577
Yeah, it's a cool experience so far and I like the, I don't know, the nice little one-on-one AMAs are really sweet.

13
00:01:05,117 --> 00:01:08,600
So I guess we'll just jump into it here and then we'll pull some questions from chat.

14
00:01:10,980 --> 00:01:15,222
How does game composition differ from other areas of music composition?

15
00:01:16,082 --> 00:01:21,924
Oh gosh, great question. Game composition is kind of like a really different philosophy,

16
00:01:21,984 --> 00:01:27,406
just at the core of it. I mean, when you're composing for a film, it's a linear experience.

17
00:01:27,466 --> 00:01:29,006
It's all pre-planned. It's...

18
00:01:29,387 --> 00:01:33,869
It's got a beginning, a middle, and an end. You're sort of composing to the dramatic beats on the

19
00:01:33,929 --> 00:01:41,093
screen, but it's a very preordained kind of thing. When you're composing for a game, it's a fluid

20
00:01:41,153 --> 00:01:45,456
experience. Everything depends upon the actions of the player, so you really don't know what's

21
00:01:45,496 --> 00:01:46,976
going to happen at any given time.

22
00:01:47,477 --> 00:01:54,882
And with that, you have to construct the music in kind of a modular way. It has to be put together

23
00:01:55,183 --> 00:02:00,366
in components that can be sort of assembled and disassembled based on what's going on,

24
00:02:00,687 --> 00:02:05,851
what the player's doing, and what activities they're involved in. The game engine has to

25
00:02:05,891 --> 00:02:09,453
essentially be able to take the music apart and then put it back together in different ways.

26
00:02:09,674 --> 00:02:11,615
And that's just really interesting.

27
00:02:12,275 --> 00:02:17,259
Because as a composer, it means I'm not thinking about beginnings and middles and ends. I'm thinking

28
00:02:17,319 --> 00:02:26,707
about states of being, of activity, of thought, of action, of ways to feel in any particular moment.

29
00:02:26,787 --> 00:02:33,992
And you express that musically and then you create a whole assortment, a kind of a hodgepodge

30
00:02:34,352 --> 00:02:39,436
of those kinds of statements, those kind of musical statements that can be then

31
00:02:39,817 --> 00:02:44,939
sort of assembled into its own vocabulary, its own kind of peculiar grammar. It's really

32
00:02:44,979 --> 00:02:50,062
interesting work. A whole complicated beast because like I guess with most, I don't know,

33
00:02:50,302 --> 00:02:53,383
narrative you have that beginning and middle and your end and that's like your safety blanket,

34
00:02:53,463 --> 00:02:56,045
but not quite having that in music seems a little intimidating.

35
00:02:57,019 --> 00:03:02,962
It's true. When I first started, it was really hard to get your head around the idea of creating

36
00:03:03,022 --> 00:03:10,866
music that seems interesting and involved and has a lot to say, and yet doesn't seem to be going

37
00:03:11,127 --> 00:03:17,390
anywhere very aggressively. It isn't giving you signposts that are kind of pointing towards the

38
00:03:17,430 --> 00:03:18,731
direction that you're heading.

39
00:03:19,591 --> 00:03:25,612
Because when you do that, when you create big, like, set piece moments within a musical composition,

40
00:03:26,212 --> 00:03:31,093
then it really draws attention to itself, especially if the music was designed to loop.

41
00:03:31,673 --> 00:03:34,954
And then you can really feel the repetition happening.

42
00:03:34,974 --> 00:03:41,095
And that's a big issue to deal with, just structurally, in terms of music composition for games.

43
00:03:41,735 --> 00:03:43,656
You want to make sure that the music feels...

44
00:03:45,362 --> 00:03:50,627
Natural, and as if it were being created specifically for the gamer's experience,

45
00:03:50,647 --> 00:03:55,050
for what they're doing. You don't really want to give away the magic trick that's going on

46
00:03:55,130 --> 00:04:01,555
underneath all the mechanics that are happening. So you have to keep in mind the unique nature

47
00:04:01,836 --> 00:04:08,181
of game music when you're creating it so that it functions really well within the construct

48
00:04:08,261 --> 00:04:09,101
of gaming itself.

49
00:04:10,825 --> 00:04:16,371
So we're going to kind of segue that into a question from chat here from Sophia in chat.

50
00:04:16,571 --> 00:04:20,895
They say hello, and would like to know when you're analyzing or researching a genre for a project.

51
00:04:21,816 --> 00:04:26,340
What exactly do you kind of note down and analyze against how do you transfer that research to your music.

52
00:04:27,078 --> 00:04:34,220
Great question. Hello, Sophia. The research process is one of my favorite parts of the work that I do

53
00:04:34,441 --> 00:04:38,422
in games and it's great with the video game industry and the kind of projects you work on

54
00:04:38,462 --> 00:04:44,343
because they're so varied and some of them are really larger than life or in the speculative

55
00:04:44,403 --> 00:04:51,485
genres so you get to create epic and expansive stuff that with really intense emotional

56
00:04:51,545 --> 00:04:53,226
undercurrents and that's a lot of fun.

57
00:04:53,806 --> 00:04:59,488
And also a lot of it can be influenced by period pieces, some of it's historical, like the work I

58
00:04:59,548 --> 00:05:05,249
did on Assassin's Creed Liberation was set in 18th century New Orleans, so you had a lot of

59
00:05:05,309 --> 00:05:11,831
cultural influences there. And with that kind of project, first thing I would do is delve into

60
00:05:12,031 --> 00:05:18,733
research for understanding the story. I mean, as a part of the team creating the game, I need to

61
00:05:18,833 --> 00:05:22,895
understand the emotional content, the context of the game.

62
00:05:22,895 --> 00:05:25,637
And so I'm trying to figure out how the characters are feeling if I'm going to express that.

63
00:05:26,417 --> 00:05:38,806
Just, just as a baseline even apart from what I'm going to do musically I need to understand how everybody's feeling and and what's going on so I tried to do that kind of research and also makes me feel more a part of the team and the project

64
00:05:38,866 --> 00:05:40,948
when I'm on the same page as everybody about.

65
00:05:41,395 --> 00:05:47,559
what we're all trying to say with the project. But then apart from that, I start looking at

66
00:05:48,079 --> 00:05:53,923
is there any instrumentation that would be specific to the era, the location? Are there

67
00:05:54,264 --> 00:06:00,148
musical techniques that would have been favored by composers at the time? That kind of thing.

68
00:06:01,048 --> 00:06:04,711
That's really interesting. I did a lot of research on French Baroque.

69
00:06:05,098 --> 00:06:09,920
a musical forms for my work on Assassin's Creed Liberation because that was the music that would

70
00:06:09,940 --> 00:06:15,922
have been popular at the time that the main character was having her adventures. So it was

71
00:06:15,962 --> 00:06:23,204
important for me to do that. And of course, since she was of African American ancestry, I also tried

72
00:06:23,304 --> 00:06:29,506
very much to understand that cultural influence in her experience, you know, those wonderful

73
00:06:30,267 --> 00:06:37,391
Strong primary harmonic colors and the really fantastic rhythms and instrumentation that I had to work with there.

74
00:06:37,471 --> 00:06:49,319
So just as an example of the kind of rich source material that you can kind of dive into, Assassin's Creed Liberation was really fantastic for me.

75
00:06:49,339 --> 00:06:57,464
That'd be like a really interesting exercise and kind of stretching those research and like your different aspects of composition skills for games like that.

76
00:06:59,092 --> 00:07:02,757
To kind of merge a question from chat with something I'm curious about,

77
00:07:03,919 --> 00:07:07,043
we have a question, have you ever had to make music for a game without seeing

78
00:07:07,083 --> 00:07:09,246
what it looks like? If so, what is that process like?

79
00:07:10,247 --> 00:07:10,488
Yeah.

80
00:07:10,840 --> 00:07:17,244
Yeah, that actually happens quite a lot, more than you'd think. And I think it has a lot to do with

81
00:07:17,805 --> 00:07:23,009
the way in which game development happens. If you're creating music for a film, you tend to be

82
00:07:23,049 --> 00:07:28,793
brought in when the film is somewhere near its final cut. You're not really creating music for

83
00:07:28,813 --> 00:07:35,458
the film while it's being shot or while it's in preliminary edits. The composer needs to know

84
00:07:35,498 --> 00:07:39,381
what the final beats are, how the shots are going to go from one thing to another.

85
00:07:39,730 --> 00:07:45,892
But for games, the game tends to be very fluid and in development when I'm brought in.

86
00:07:46,272 --> 00:07:49,293
And sometimes there really isn't even anything playable yet.

87
00:07:49,633 --> 00:07:55,495
Or if there is, it's really early character designs with the arms jutting straight out

88
00:07:55,535 --> 00:08:01,177
and just sort of floating over some sort of really abstract looking geometrical grid.

89
00:08:01,237 --> 00:08:05,118
And it gives me no idea of what the game's going to look like or feel like.

90
00:08:05,579 --> 00:08:13,245
And you have to be able to sort of cope with that, kind of plumb the depths of your own imagination to kind of fill in those gaps.

91
00:08:13,285 --> 00:08:28,458
So that's why research really does help a lot there, because we have to kind of bring our own inner life to the envisioning of what it is we're scoring when we don't have those kinds of visual helpers to guide us along.

92
00:08:29,828 --> 00:08:33,770
So kind of in the same vein of that, Christian in chat wants to know,

93
00:08:34,110 --> 00:08:38,072
how do you ensure that sound effects and music really mesh together really well and form a

94
00:08:38,232 --> 00:08:42,995
consistent experience as opposed to just kind of like a random mix that doesn't jar quite well?

95
00:08:43,835 --> 00:08:47,216
Yeah, that's a great question, Christian. And I think

96
00:08:47,647 --> 00:08:53,011
The best way to go about that is to have a really nice working relationship between the composer and

97
00:08:53,051 --> 00:08:56,994
the sound designer, the sound team, the audio director. We're all kind of on the same page

98
00:08:57,014 --> 00:09:02,899
and we're working together. And sometimes it's trial and error. The sound design team may not

99
00:09:03,039 --> 00:09:07,602
actually know what the sound effects are going to be doing when they ask me to compose the music.

100
00:09:07,782 --> 00:09:12,606
I might be ahead of them in terms of the workflow and I deliver music for them and then they

101
00:09:12,646 --> 00:09:14,447
experiment with the sound design and

102
00:09:14,827 --> 00:09:18,810
They come back to me and ask me to kind of tweak things if they're not sort of fitting

103
00:09:18,850 --> 00:09:23,373
together properly with the sort of sound design decisions that they're making for the game.

104
00:09:23,893 --> 00:09:27,235
Or on the other hand, sometimes they've just gone ahead and changed what they were doing

105
00:09:27,275 --> 00:09:29,417
to fit the music that I was delivering it.

106
00:09:29,597 --> 00:09:33,219
I think it depends on priorities, on what people are happy with.

107
00:09:33,919 --> 00:09:35,961
It's such a collaborative process.

108
00:09:36,041 --> 00:09:41,984
It's just so very fluid and it's about personalities and artistic ambitions.

109
00:09:42,825 --> 00:09:46,847
And everybody's trying very hard to make sure all the elements come together.

110
00:09:46,867 --> 00:09:52,671
It's so a conglomeration of so many different creative strategies.

111
00:09:52,871 --> 00:09:57,193
And so I think that's part of what makes game development so exciting.

112
00:09:57,253 --> 00:09:59,795
So many different viewpoints coming together.

113
00:10:01,463 --> 00:10:07,314
Just to expand on that, how long is your typical involvement in a project from your very first

114
00:10:08,136 --> 00:10:10,541
plucking at strings to the final composition delivered to them?

115
00:10:10,621 --> 00:10:12,745
How long are you working alongside those developers?

116
00:10:13,598 --> 00:10:16,618
Oh, great. That is a great question because it's hard to answer.

117
00:10:17,119 --> 00:10:18,899
It really depends on the project.

118
00:10:18,939 --> 00:10:24,440
I mean, I've been on indie teams that are really short development schedule.

119
00:10:24,520 --> 00:10:28,641
And I'm kind of in there hitting the ground running, just cranking out the tracks.

120
00:10:28,701 --> 00:10:30,261
And it's just maybe a month or so

121
00:10:31,401 --> 00:10:32,982
where I've completed all the work for it.

122
00:10:33,202 --> 00:10:35,622
And on the other end of the spectrum, I've been in projects

123
00:10:35,642 --> 00:10:38,063
that have had me working on and off for years.

124
00:10:40,354 --> 00:10:49,561
While they're developing and they'll come to me and ask me to deliver kind of a cache of tracks for them to incorporate based on where the game is at that time.

125
00:10:49,581 --> 00:10:54,684
And then they'll go off and they'll develop and they'll work on the project and it'll be very fluid.

126
00:10:54,724 --> 00:11:00,308
They'll come back to me and say things like, oh, the game's completely different now, so we need you to revise the music in this way or that way.

127
00:11:00,789 --> 00:11:11,183
Or we're thinking about a different style or this level is how now has been removed and we're now doing something different. So we're repurposing music in a different way and we need you to deliver music in a different.

128
00:11:12,114 --> 00:11:17,537
feeling or structured in a different way. The interactive implementation scheme may have changed.

129
00:11:18,318 --> 00:11:25,202
That's very challenging and very interesting work. There are a lot of different pitfalls to it,

130
00:11:25,242 --> 00:11:32,286
but also some really great things can come out of it. It stretches you as a composer, makes you

131
00:11:32,586 --> 00:11:41,071
grow and look to yourself to think of different kinds of solutions to problems. That can be a lot

132
00:11:41,111 --> 00:11:41,352
of fun.

133
00:11:43,191 --> 00:11:47,055
Another question from chat here from Brian on themes and thematic development.

134
00:11:47,175 --> 00:11:52,779
Any suggestions on incorporating recognizable themes into content without getting samey or redundant through overuse?

135
00:11:54,060 --> 00:11:55,322
Good question. Yeah.

136
00:11:56,621 --> 00:12:03,203
Themes are tricky in video games, particularly with looping content, or content that's going

137
00:12:03,223 --> 00:12:09,726
to be repeated a lot. I mean, you can be hundreds of hours playing a game, and there are only a few

138
00:12:09,766 --> 00:12:16,168
games that are actually requisitioning hundreds of hours of music. So there's going to be repetition

139
00:12:16,188 --> 00:12:21,730
happening there, and it's a good point that you have to be very aware of that as an aspect of

140
00:12:22,611 --> 00:12:25,594
I kind of like to break themes down.

141
00:12:25,734 --> 00:12:29,437
I mean, you state them in a very recognizable and dynamic way

142
00:12:30,298 --> 00:12:33,000
when it's important at a set piece moment in the game,

143
00:12:33,081 --> 00:12:36,123
or maybe it's a part of the main theme, or it's a part of a main menu,

144
00:12:36,163 --> 00:12:41,088
and you really want to use it as a way in which you're creating a musical signature for the project.

145
00:12:41,448 --> 00:12:49,374
But then you can break it down into fragments like motives, small segments, just a few notes,

146
00:12:49,655 --> 00:12:53,297
something that might not even be consciously recognized as a part of that theme.

147
00:12:53,898 --> 00:12:56,219
And then you can sprinkle it elsewhere.

148
00:12:56,240 --> 00:13:00,303
And it just communicates in a subconscious way to the player.

149
00:13:00,803 --> 00:13:05,346
It asserts the game's musical identity without really being overt about it.

150
00:13:05,886 --> 00:13:09,489
And you can also use them as figures, ostinatos.

151
00:13:09,549 --> 00:13:13,871
You can restructure a theme to be more of an underlying pattern

152
00:13:14,272 --> 00:13:17,234
that other original material might be on top of.

153
00:13:17,574 --> 00:13:22,377
And that's a way to also assert the theme without it being a foreground element.

154
00:13:22,477 --> 00:13:26,139
It's not something that is going to be front of consciousness,

155
00:13:26,239 --> 00:13:27,840
but it's still going to be there.

156
00:13:27,920 --> 00:13:30,402
It's going to be asserting an identity.

157
00:13:30,622 --> 00:13:33,404
And I think that's always a great thing to try to strive for,

158
00:13:34,244 --> 00:13:37,305
to sprinkle a sense of identity into everything you're doing.

159
00:13:37,326 --> 00:13:40,887
That kind of builds into a question from Nikki in chat.

160
00:13:41,127 --> 00:13:42,588
Do you have a favorite leaf motif?

161
00:13:43,048 --> 00:13:43,949
If so, what is it?

162
00:13:44,189 --> 00:13:45,269
Kind of what's the formula for that?

163
00:13:46,470 --> 00:13:46,970
Oh, gosh.

164
00:13:47,791 --> 00:13:52,233
In terms of, well, the Assassin's Creed Liberation Score

165
00:13:52,293 --> 00:13:55,675
was really strongly driven by leitmotifs.

166
00:13:55,775 --> 00:13:56,675
I had them for,

167
00:13:58,033 --> 00:14:04,316
Nearly every character, every one of the important characters, because there are so many, but all of the main characters had

168
00:14:05,337 --> 00:14:12,980
leitmotifs that returned and I couldn't tell you if there was a favorite leitmotif that I've used for a project.

169
00:14:13,940 --> 00:14:21,884
Although I do have to say that I had a lot of fun with the leitmotif, the core leitmotif for Spore Hero for Electronic Arts.

170
00:14:22,664 --> 00:14:26,006
Because that was an opportunity to express it in so many different ways.

171
00:14:26,386 --> 00:14:30,388
Spore Hero was a score that was very influenced by world music.

172
00:14:30,488 --> 00:14:36,051
It's, after all, it's a game about monsters wandering around a primitive world.

173
00:14:36,111 --> 00:14:40,274
And so I really wanted you to feel this sort of friendly world music atmosphere.

174
00:14:40,314 --> 00:14:43,515
And I was delving into all different kinds of world music for it.

175
00:14:43,555 --> 00:14:48,378
So taking the core theme, the leitmotif that's first expressed in the main theme,

176
00:14:48,418 --> 00:14:48,878
and then just...

177
00:14:49,319 --> 00:14:55,301
Re-expressing it in all of these different cultural, musical styles and influences was

178
00:14:55,501 --> 00:15:00,223
tremendous fun. All kinds of different instruments, all kinds of different rhythmic constructs. And

179
00:15:00,783 --> 00:15:06,785
it just, it made it a really fun puzzle for me to see how many different ways you can kind of

180
00:15:06,845 --> 00:15:11,827
turn a theme inside out and rediscover it as a composer and see what it can do.

181
00:15:13,414 --> 00:15:18,378
Building that into a question from Tim, who says hello and thank you for answering our questions.

182
00:15:18,859 --> 00:15:22,142
What is your process to avoid overcomposing a section or scene in game?

183
00:15:22,222 --> 00:15:24,284
Can you share examples of how you've done that in the past?

184
00:15:25,442 --> 00:15:46,700
Mm, good point. Yeah, you don't, it's like a fine line. You don't want to do too little, you don't want to do too much. If the music is too aggressive, it can really start to feel aggressively dominant in the experience you're having in the game. And you certainly don't want that. For Assassin's Creed Liberation, I had a four chord

185
00:15:47,821 --> 00:15:53,323
Essentially it's a theme, but it's also just a four chord pattern. Very subtle, but it was

186
00:15:53,863 --> 00:15:59,004
something that was incorporated as essentially the central building block of the main theme

187
00:15:59,044 --> 00:16:02,685
of the game. This four chord pattern that repeated over and over and over again.

188
00:16:02,705 --> 00:16:09,407
And I was able to use that a lot in the game. And one of the virtues of it was that it was

189
00:16:09,667 --> 00:16:11,688
very subtle, very low keyed.

190
00:16:12,828 --> 00:16:17,710
Almost subliminal in the sense that you could recognize it when it came back,

191
00:16:18,130 --> 00:16:22,372
but it wasn't really anything that would really arrest your attention.

192
00:16:22,952 --> 00:16:29,155
And so it was this stealth music, just functionally speaking, for a stealth game.

193
00:16:29,195 --> 00:16:36,677
But functionally speaking, it was a stealthy construct that I could use to create a sense

194
00:16:36,697 --> 00:16:40,319
of identity without having to overwrite the piece.

195
00:16:41,169 --> 00:16:48,935
in order to use a lot of really dynamic thematic ideas that would arrest the player's attention more aggressively.

196
00:16:50,457 --> 00:16:55,541
So you've talked a little bit already about how you kind of do your research to get into

197
00:16:55,581 --> 00:16:59,344
like the period and spirit of the game, but what about genres in that sense?

198
00:16:59,384 --> 00:17:03,327
When you're researching for scores that you're not already deeply knowledgeable in the genre,

199
00:17:03,367 --> 00:17:07,250
what's your immersion approach and when do you know you're ready to dive into creating

200
00:17:07,270 --> 00:17:08,911
something unique with your new material?

201
00:17:08,931 --> 00:17:11,093
And that's a question from Brian, I don't want to steal credit for that one.

202
00:17:11,934 --> 00:17:17,680
Brian, nice question. And that is definitely something that we have to face a lot. I mean,

203
00:17:18,361 --> 00:17:21,845
if you're doing pretty well as a game composer, you're probably going to be

204
00:17:22,405 --> 00:17:28,312
scoring projects from a lot of different kind of game genres. And that can be pretty challenging.

205
00:17:28,372 --> 00:17:31,776
I remember when I was first hired to do the music for Speed Racer,

206
00:17:32,836 --> 00:17:38,399
I had to really look into what the musical scores are like for racing games.

207
00:17:38,499 --> 00:17:42,881
It's very techno-driven music, and that wasn't something I had done up to that point.

208
00:17:43,622 --> 00:17:49,485
So I got a chance to learn something really new and to kind of dive into the electronic sound palette

209
00:17:49,525 --> 00:17:51,946
and those really driving rhythms.

210
00:17:52,613 --> 00:17:59,437
And that really dominant beat that just helps to accentuate the sense of speed in a racing game.

211
00:17:59,477 --> 00:18:01,359
So that was something I got to learn along the way.

212
00:18:02,480 --> 00:18:07,203
On the other hand, it was also tied into the speed racer intellectual property and the

213
00:18:07,623 --> 00:18:14,250
Wachowski's film that had just come out at the time. So it was, it had to have this very eccentric

214
00:18:14,650 --> 00:18:20,896
and almost retro feel. And I, so I had this sort of juggle and, and, and merge together two ideas

215
00:18:20,916 --> 00:18:28,604
that were really opposite, a very retro inspired orchestral score with this very techno driving

216
00:18:28,684 --> 00:18:31,187
genre that we, that really needed to be.

217
00:18:32,368 --> 00:18:33,869
I had to be true to it.

218
00:18:33,989 --> 00:18:38,613
It is a racing game and you don't want to disappoint fans of racing games.

219
00:18:38,713 --> 00:18:42,997
I mean, there's an expectation there and if the musical score is so different

220
00:18:43,017 --> 00:18:47,941
that it doesn't seem to have the spirit of the genre running through it,

221
00:18:48,422 --> 00:18:52,145
then it can start to feel like the music's sitting on top of the game

222
00:18:52,425 --> 00:18:54,507
and not really woven into it.

223
00:18:54,767 --> 00:18:57,549
And I didn't want that to happen with Speed Racer.

224
00:18:58,283 --> 00:19:05,348
I ended up with this really eccentric amalgamation of styles and influences, and it was a lot

225
00:19:05,388 --> 00:19:05,768
of fun.

226
00:19:05,788 --> 00:19:07,990
I had a really good time working on that one.

