00:26:35,161 --> 00:26:41,663
Good one, yeah. Well, it's been my experience that that can vary really wildly depending upon

309
00:26:41,703 --> 00:26:45,564
the type of team you're working with. If you're working with an indie team, you may be working

310
00:26:45,645 --> 00:26:52,967
with the grand poobah, you know, the game director, the game designer, someone with that title

311
00:26:53,007 --> 00:26:58,169
producer you might be working with. Sometimes if you're working with one of the larger publishers,

312
00:26:58,189 --> 00:27:02,590
you'll also be working with a producer because the music is being requisitioned by the publisher

313
00:27:02,670 --> 00:27:04,211
and not by the development team. So,

314
00:27:04,665 --> 00:27:23,655
The publisher has a producer who's specifically assigned to oversee your work and make sure everything's on track. On the other hand, if you're working with the development studio itself, sometimes it's an audio director, if you have a well thought out team for audio within that developer.

315
00:27:24,165 --> 00:27:35,428
It might be the audio director, might be a sound designer if it's a smaller development team and they don't really have a lot of audio folks. It just might be the sole audio person on that team you're talking to.

316
00:27:36,208 --> 00:27:45,670
And there have been projects I've worked on who they've had nobody on audio at all and I've been talking to maybe a programmer or something like that.

317
00:27:46,470 --> 00:27:53,112
So it really does depend upon the structure of the development team itself as to who you're going to be talking to.

